application.effects.after: Effects triggered last in the processing chain of any user request. Useful for finalizing logic — such as registering observers that should wait for specific conditions to trigger later.
application.effects.before: Effects triggered first in the processing chain of any user request. Ideal for preparing context — for example, setting global variables based on the current participant, screen, etc., which will be used across many interactions.
application.effects.init: Effects applied to each chat instance upon creation. Useful for setting up initial chat configuration and global states.
screen.effects.after: Effects triggered for any user request on this screen, executed right after the request's own effects and before the application's after-effects. Useful for screen-specific postprocessing logic.
screen.effects.before: Effects triggered for any user request on this screen, executed right after the application's before-effects and before the specific request's effects. Good place for screen-specific preconditions or shared logic.
screen.effects.init: Effects triggered each time the screen is activated. Suitable for setting up initial screen state if needed.
